Room was ok, it was clean, spacious & at the end of the hall on the top floor, so it was quiet. She mumbles & neither of us heard her, so I asked her to please repeat herself, this time she gets loud & starts speaking slowly to us that "it's...at...the...top...of... the...stairs", I was so mad, I had to walk away before I told her off. It was the only place open so we got cheese pizzas & went to our room, we don't drink, but 5 hrs later we were both sick & spent our 2nd day in bed minus a trip to get meds & reschedule our hot springs trip.

Needless to say we won't be back. If you're seeking a relaxing break from the city, to play some poker & be treated like a guest instead of a burden, then go anywhere but here.

reviews.text:
The Hotel Colorado definitely has that old-world charm youâre looking for - the history here is incredible and you can really feel the stories in these walls. We even ended up with an impromptu ghost tour from other guests our first night, which was actually pretty fun and added to the whole historic atmosphere.

Unfortunately, things went downhill on day two when our room became overrun with mosquitos and gnats. The culprit seems to be the window AC units combined with zero ventilation in the bathroom. To get any airflow, you have to open the windows, but the old cranking mechanisms have gaps that let bugs pour right in.

By the second night, the master bedroom was swarming with flying insects. We spent way too much time swatting bugs and ended up having to kill several right on the bedding (photos attached).

The morning that we checked out, we even had our tub full of uninvited guests.

If we were staying at some remote cabin in the wilderness, Iâd expect this kind of thing, but not at whatâs supposed to be one of Glenwood Springsâ premier hotels.

The historic character is genuinely cool, but the practical issues with the rooms really detracted from what should have been a special stay. For the price point and reputation, the bug situation needs to be addressed - better sealing around windows and proper bathroom ventilation would go a long way.ââââââââââââââââ
